{"title_page": "Alex Paton (physician)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox medical person\n|honorific_prefix=\n|name        = Alexander Paton\n|image       = \n|alt         = \n|caption     = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1924|03|02|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Allahabad]], India\n|death_date  = {{Death date and age|2015|09|12|1924|03|02|df=y}}\n|death_place = \n|death_cause = \n|nationality = British\n|education   = {{ubl|[[Alleyn Court Prep School]]|[[Canford School]], Dorset|[[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]]}}\n|occupation  = [[Physician]]\n|years_active= \n|known_for   = {{ubl|[[London medical students at Belsen]]|Study of the effects of [[alcoholic liver cirrhosis]]|Postgraduate [[Dean (education)|Dean]]|First chairman of the medical committee of [[Alcohol Change UK|Alcohol Concern]]}}\n|field       = \n|work_institutions = {{ubl|[[City Hospital, Birmingham|Dudley Road Hospital]]|[[North West London Hospitals NHS Trust|North-West London hospitals]]|[[St Ann's Hospital]]}}\n|specialism  = [[Gastroenterology]]\n|research_field = [[Alcohol misuse]]\n|notable_works  = ''ABC of Alcohol''\n}}\n'''Alexander Paton''' (2 March 1924 \u2013 12 September 2015) was a British [[gastroenterologist]], writer and postgraduate [[Dean (education)|dean]] for [[North West London Hospitals NHS Trust|North-West London hospitals]], who was a specialist in [[alcohol misuse]].\n\nIn 1945, while studying medicine at [[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]], he was one of the [[London medical students at Belsen|London medical students]] who were sent to [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp]] shortly after its liberation by British troops, to assist in administering the \"starvation diet\" to the severely malnourished and dying inmates.\n\nPaton was one of the first intake of doctors into the British [[National Health Service]] and later became a registrar to [[Sheila Sherlock]], a recognised authority on liver disease. In 1959, he was appointed consultant physician to [[City Hospital, Birmingham|Dudley Road Hospital]], Birmingham, where he taught medical students for the [[Membership of the Royal Colleges of Physicians of the United Kingdom|MRCP]], established an [[endoscopy]] service and began a 20-year study of the effects of [[alcoholic liver cirrhosis]].\n\nHe later held consultant positions at the [[St Ann's Hospital]] and the Prince of Wales Hospital in North London, and became the first chairman of the medical committee of [[Alcohol Change UK|Alcohol Concern]]. His book, ''ABC of Alcohol'', went through four editions.\n\n==Early life==\nAlexander Paton was born on 2 March 1924 in [[Allahabad]], India. His father, also called Alex, was an army colonel who had been awarded the [[Military Cross]]. His mother, Isabel Sybil Emma Grimwood Mears was the daughter of Sir [[Edward Grimwood Mears]], chief justice of the [[High Court of Allahabad]].<ref name=\"MunksRoll\">{{Cite web|url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/7146|title=Munks Roll Details for Alexander Paton|last=|first=|date=|website=munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter completing his early education at [[Alleyn Court Prep School]], Essex, he gained a scholarship to [[Canford School]] in Dorset and subsequently gained admission to study medicine at [[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]], London during [[The Blitz]].<ref name=\"MunksRoll\"/><ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/sep/27/alex-paton-obituary|title=Alex Paton obituary|last=Richmond|first=Caroline|date=27 September 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=4 September 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\"BMJObituary\">{{Cite journal|last=Jain|first=Stephan|date=24 September 2015|title=Re: Alexander Paton|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/351/bmj.h5123/rr-5|journal=British Medical Journal|language=en|volume=351|pages=h5123|doi=10.1136/bmj.h5123|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Belsen==\n[[File:Group photo of London Medical students who went to Belsen Wellcome L0029073.jpg|thumb|Group photo of London Medical students who went to Belsen]]\nHe was one of the London medical students who were sent to [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp]] in 1945, shortly after its liberation by the British troops, to assist [[Arnold Peter Meiklejohn]] in administering what was known as the \"starvation diet\" to the severely malnourished and dying inmates. Many of these inmates had such advanced malnutrition that they were intolerant of large, highly nutritious meals and the diet comprised small, frequent, bland meals which were much better tolerated.<ref name=Shepherd2005>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=FJ8h0vOBPR8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Student+volunteer+for+medical+relief+at+the+concentration+camp+Bergen-Belsen#v=onepage&q=student&f=false|title=AfterDaybreak: The Liberation of Belsen, 1945|last=Shephard|first=Ben|date=2005|page=130|publisher=Random House|isbn=9781409079644|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn his memoirs, published in the ''British Medical Journal'' in 1981,<ref name=MunksRoll/> he described how on 4 April 1945 there was a proposed trip to Holland for 12 St Thomas's students. He put his name down and on 12 April was at the [[The Landmark London|Hotel Grand Central at Marylebone]] collecting his kit. After a briefing by [[Richard Doll]], explaining how they were to feed the starving Dutch with an experimental mixture, they were asked to \"keep detailed records\".<ref name=\"Paton1981\">{{Cite journal|last=Patton|first=Aex|date=December 1981|title=Mission to Belsen 1945|journal=British Medical Journal|volume=283|issue=6307|pages=1656\u20131659|pmc=1507476|pmid=6797597|doi=10.1136/bmj.283.6307.1656}}</ref><ref name=Belsen>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bergenbelsen.co.uk/pages/Database/ReliefStaffAccount.asp?HeroesID=44&=44|title=Paton|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bergenbelsen.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Paton2005\">{{Cite journal|last=Paton|first=Alex|date=30 April 2005|title=After Daybreak: The Liberation of Belsen, 1945|journal=BMJ: British Medical Journal|volume=330|issue=7498|pages=1030|issn=0959-8138|pmc=557164|doi=10.1136/bmj.330.7498.1030}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April, they were informed that the destination had changed to Belsen and they were rushed to [[Cirencester]], where they spent three \u201cfrustrating\u201d days. He recalled how the newspapers had already announced that \u201c100 students from nine London medical schools are being rushed to Germany\u201d. They arrived in Belsen on 2 May 1945 and on the following day began to clean up the huts in the camp and supervise feeding of inmates.<ref name=\"Paton1981\"/><ref name=Belsen/><ref name=\"Paton2005\"/>\n\nWith another student [[A. T. Cook]], they were one of the first to create a hospital from a hut.<ref name=Vella1984>{{Cite journal|last=Vella|first=E. E.|date=1984|title=Belsen: Medical Aspects of a World War 11 Concentration Camp|url=https://jramc.bmj.com/content/jramc/130/1/34.full.pdf|journal=[[Royal Army Medical Corps#Journal|Journal Royal Army Medical Corps]]|volume=130|issue=1|pages=34\u201359|via=|doi=10.1136/jramc-130-01-08|pmid=6371230}}</ref>\n\nUpon return, he landed at [[Croydon airport|Croydon]] on 29 May 1945 \u201cwith feelings that are too complicated to analyse at the moment\u201d.<ref name=Shepherd2005/><ref name=\"Paton1981\"/>\n\n==Career==\nPaton qualified in 1947 and was one of the first intake of doctors into the new [[NHS]].<ref name=Haga>{{Cite web|url=http://www.haga.co.uk/remembering-alex-paton/|title=Remembering Alex Paton|last=|first=|date=12 September 2016|website=HAGA|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 September 2019}}</ref>  After house officer posts he spent two years\u2019 doing national service in the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]] in [[Trieste]].  Following a post in [[Salisbury]] in 1950, and another at [[St Helier Hospital]] in 1951,<ref name=MunksRoll/> he became registrar to [[Sheila Sherlock]],<ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/> an expert in liver disease, at the [[Royal Postgraduate Medical School]], part of the [[Hammersmith Hospital]]. At his interview with Sherlock, she asked Paton \"are you prepared to push patients in a bed to the laboratory? You are? The job is yours\".<ref name=Richmond2002>{{Cite journal|last=Richmond|first=Caroline|date=19 January 2002|title=Dame Sheila Sherlock|journal=BMJ: British Medical Journal|volume=324|issue=7330|pages=174|issn=0959-8138|pmc=1122088|doi=10.1136/bmj.324.7330.174}}</ref> During this post, he kept a private diary in which he wrote about the research into liver disease, saying... \"we and anyone else at Hammersmith use subjects for experiments who will not necessarily benefit by them\"<ref name=Seldon2017>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iGOhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT169|title=TheWhistle-Blower: The Life of Maurice Pappworth: the story of one man's battle against the medical establishment|last=Seldon|first=Joanna|date=2017|publisher=University of Buckingham Press|isbn=9781-908684974|location=Buckingham|pages=|language=en|chapter=5. Breaking the Silence: A Rebel and his Cause}}</ref> and quoted his South African houseman as saying \"the beds are nothing more than an annexe to the medical laboratories\".<ref name=Hazelgrove2004>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NgvQHQqA1HkC&pg=PA188|title=Twentiethcentury ethics of human subjects research: historical perspectives on values, practices, and regulations|last=Hazelgrove|first=Jenny|date=2004|publisher=Franz Steiner Verlag|isbn=9783515084550|editor-last=Roelcke|editor-first=Volker|location=|pages=188|language=en|chapter=British Research Ethics after the Second World War: The Controversy at the British Postgraduate Medical School, Hammersmith Hospital}}</ref><ref nameO'Mahony2019>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ynJfDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT43|title=Can Medicine Be Cured?: The Corruption of a Profession|last=O'Mahony|first=Seamus|date=2019|publisher=Head of Zeus Ltd|isbn=9781788544535|location=|pages=|language=en|chapter=3. Fifty Golden Years}}</ref>\n\nHe completed his [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]] at [[Yale University]] on the topic of neurology in [[diabetes mellitus]].<ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/> In 1959, he was appointed consultant physician  to [[City Hospital, Birmingham|Dudley Road Hospital]], Birmingham, where his main focus was on [[emergency medicine]],<ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/> [[internal medicine]] and the liver.<ref name=\"BMJObituary\"/> Here he taught postgraduate medical students who were preparing for the [[Membership of the Royal Colleges of Physicians of the United Kingdom|MRCP]] examination, established an [[endoscopy]] service and began a 20-year study of the effects of [[alcoholic liver cirrhosis]].<ref name=MunksRoll/><ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/>\n\nIn 1973, he took a one-year [[sabbatical]] as a visiting professor of medicine in [[Baghdad]].<ref name=MunksRoll/><ref name=Haga/>\n\nIn 1981 he returned to London and became postgraduate [[Dean (education)|Dean]] for [[North West London Hospitals NHS Trust|North-West London hospitals]].<ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/> He took up consultant positions at the [[St Ann's Hospital]] and the Prince of Wales Hospital in North London, and became the first chairman of the medical committee of [[Alcohol Change UK|Alcohol Concern]].<ref name=MunksRoll/>\n\nIn the ''British Medical Journal'''s ''[[BMJ ABC Series|ABC of Alcohol]]'', which he edited,<ref name=Haga/> Paton described people's patterns of drinking and its association with genetic, constitutional and environmental factors, and explained why women were more susceptible to the effects of alcohol than men.<ref name=\"Moriarty\"/> In addition he highlighted how alcohol misuse was easily missed in the elderly.<ref name=\"Moriarty\">{{Cite journal|last=Moriarty|first=Kieran|date=January 2006|title=ABC of Alcohol (4th edn)|journal=Annals of the Royal College of Surgeons of England|language=en|volume=88|issue=1|pages=84\u201385|doi=10.1308/rcsann.2006.88.1.84b|pmc=1963615}}</ref><ref name=cisa>{{Cite web|url=http://en.cisa.org.br/artigo/89/the-absorption-of-alcohol-in-the.php|title=The absorption of alcohol in the body|last=Paton|first=Alex|date=|website=en.cisa.org.br|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn reviewing the book ''Medical Nemesis'' by [[Ivan Illich]], he was one of the few reviewers supporting Illich, saying that \u201chis argument is closely reasoned, sometimes obscure, often exasperating, but never dull, and fully documented\u201d.<ref name=RCSEdin2016>{{Cite journal|last=O\u2019Mahony|first=S.|date=2016|title=Medical Nemesis 40 years on: the enduring legacy of Ivan Illich|url=https://www.rcpe.ac.uk/sites/default/files/jrcpe_46_2_omahony_0.pdf|journal=Royal College of Physicians Edinburgh|volume=46|issue=2|pages=134\u2013139|via=|doi=10.4997/JRCPE.2016.214|pmid=27929580}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, he retired and for the next three years worked at the addictions unit at the [[Warneford Hospital]], Oxford.<ref name=MunksRoll/>\n\n==Other roles==\nPaton was a member of the Association of Physicians, the [[Medical Research Society]], Haringey Health Authority, the scholarship committee of the Wingate Foundation, the [[Pensions Appeal Tribunal]] of which he later became chairman, and the [[Royal College of Physicians]] of which he was examiner and regional adviser. For seven years he was secretary of the West Midlands Physicians Association. He also chaired the travelling fellowships committee of the [[King\u2019s Fund]].<ref name=MunksRoll/>\n\n==Personal and family==\nIn 1947 he married Phyllis Ann Jennifer Pepys, better known as Ann, a nurse and descendant of [[Samuel Pepys]]' cousin and [[Sir Lucas Pepys]].<ref name=MunksRoll/><ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/> They later retired to rural Oxfordshire together.<ref name=MunksRoll/> [[Margaret Tempest]] became his step-grand mother in 1951, when she married his grandfather.<ref name=MunksRoll/><ref name=Russen>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipswichstar.co.uk/news/ipswich-icons-artist-margaret-mary-tempest-brought-little-grey-rabbit-to-life-1-4805930|title=Ipswich Icons - Artist Margaret Mary Tempest brought Little Grey Rabbit to life|last=Russen|first=Mervyn|date=5 December 2016|website=Ipswich Star|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=SuffolkArtists>{{Cite web|url=https://suffolkartists.co.uk/index.cgi?choice=painter&pid=787|title=Suffolk Artists - TEMPEST, Margaret Mary|last=|first=|date=|website=suffolkartists.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=Paton>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandscoxcharity.uk/alexander-paton|title=Alexander Paton|last=Paton|first=Alexander|date=|website=Sands Cox Charity|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe played tennis, enjoyed climbing, skiing, walking, classical music, the arts, photography, natural history, church architecture and travelling. He visited [[Antarctica]] twice.<ref name=MunksRoll/>\n\nOne son, Charles, died in 1973 and his wife Ann died in 2008.<ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/> They had two other sons, Alex and Anthony, and two daughters, Clare and Rachel.<ref name=MunksRoll/>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nPaton died on 12 September 2015.<ref name=MunksRoll/><ref name=\"BMJObituary\"/>\n\nHis memoirs are included in the 2005 book ''After Daybreak: The Liberation of Belsen, 1945'' by [[Ben Shephard (historian)|Ben Shephard]].<ref name=\"Paton2005\"/> He was portrayed in the 2007 feature-length drama titled ''[[The Relief of Belsen]]'' in which he quotes \"in my hut there were no deaths today, sir\".<ref name=\"IMBb\">{{Citation|last=|first=|title=The Relief of Belsen|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0950502/characters/nm2447755?ref_=tt_cl_t11|volume=|pages=|access-date=4 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=BFI>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2bd9c0d0e0|title=Henry Pettigrew|last=|first=|date=|website=[[British Film Institute]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\nPaton wrote a number of articles for newspapers, edited work in the ''British Medical Journal'' for 50 years and was a member of [[Stephen Lock]]'s BMJ writing workshops. He also wrote and edited the BMJ's publication ''ABC of Alcohol'', which went through four editions.<ref name=MunksRoll/> On the confusion between 'effect' and 'affect', he wrote \"these words are commonly used, and misuse may seriously affect (alter) meaning\".<ref name=Goodman2014>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1KsZBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA75&dq=liver+disease+alex+paton#v=onepage&q=liver%20disease%20alex%20paton&f=false|title=MedicalWriting|last=Goodman|first=Neville W.|last2=Edwards|first2=Martin B.|date=2014|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=9781107628151|edition=4th|location=|pages=75|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHis time in Baghdad led him to write about the [[Marsh Arabs]].<ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/>\n\n===Articles===\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 7832842 | doi=10.1136/bmj.309.6949.249 | volume=309 | title=Prescribing selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors as strategy for prevention of suicide | pmc=2540780 | year=1994 | journal=BMJ | pages=249\u201353 | last1 = Freemantle | first1 = N | last2 = House | first2 = A | last3 = Song | first3 = F | last4 = Mason | first4 = JM | last5 = Sheldon | first5 = TA}}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.1093/alcalc/34.4.502 | volume=34 | title=REFLECTIONS ON ALCOHOL AND THE YOUNG | year=1999 | journal=Alcohol and Alcoholism | pages=502\u2013505 | last1 = Paton | first1 = A.}}\n*{{cite journal | pmid = 15637372 | doi=10.1136/bmj.330.7482.85 | volume=330 | title=Alcohol in the body | pmc=543875 | year=2005 | journal=BMJ | pages=85\u20137 | last1 = Paton | first1 = A}}\n*{{cite journal | doi = 10.12968/hosp.2000.61.3.1290 | volume=61 | title=Alcohol: matters of life and death | year=2000 | journal=Hospital Medicine | pages=156\u2013157 | last1 = Paton | first1 = Alex}}\n\n===Books===\n*''Liver Disease''. [[Heinemann (publisher)|William Heinemann]], London, 1969. {{ISBN|0433247207}}\n*''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=AXvAY3ewtQQC&lpg=PP1&dq=alex%20paton%20gastroenterology&pg=PP4#v=onepage&q&f=false ABC of Alcohol]''. [[Blackwell Publishing]], Oxford, 1982. (Four editions, co-edited with Robin Touquet)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/?term=Alex+paton ''British Medical Journal'' articles by Paton]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paton, Alex (physician)}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Allahabad]]\n[[Category:20th-century British medical doctors]]\n[[Category:British gastroenterologists]]\n[[Category:London medical students who assisted at Belsen]]\n[[Category:1945 in medicine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox medical person\n|honorific_prefix=\n|name        = Alexander Paton\n|image       = \n|alt         = \n|caption     = \n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1924|03|02|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Allahabad]], India\n|death_date  = {{Death date and age|2015|09|12|1924|03|02|df=y}}\n|death_place = \n|death_cause = \n|nationality = British\n|education   = {{ubl|[[Alleyn Court Prep School]]|[[Canford School]], Dorset|[[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]]}}\n|occupation  = [[Physician]]\n|years_active= \n|known_for   = {{ubl|[[London medical students at Belsen]]|Study of the effects of [[alcoholic liver cirrhosis]]|Postgraduate [[Dean (education)|Dean]]|First chairman of the medical committee of [[Alcohol Change UK|Alcohol Concern]]}}\n|field       = \n|work_institutions = {{ubl|[[City Hospital, Birmingham|Dudley Road Hospital]]|[[North West London Hospitals NHS Trust|North-West London hospitals]]|[[St Ann's Hospital]]}}\n|specialism  = [[Gastroenterology]]\n|research_field = [[Alcohol misuse]]\n|notable_works  = ''ABC of Alcohol''\n}}\n'''Alexander Paton''' (2 March 1924 \u2013 12 September 2015) was a British [[gastroenterologist]], writer and postgraduate [[Dean (education)|dean]] for [[North West London Hospitals NHS Trust|North-West London hospitals]], who was a specialist in [[alcohol misuse]].\n\nIn 1945, while studying medicine at [[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]], he was one of the [[London medical students at Belsen|London medical students]] who were sent to [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp]] shortly after its liberation by British troops, to assist in administering the \"starvation diet\" to the severely malnourished and dying inmates.\n\nPaton was one of the first intake of doctors into the British [[National Health Service]] and later became a registrar to [[Sheila Sherlock]], a recognised authority on liver disease. In 1959, he was appointed consultant physician to [[City Hospital, Birmingham|Dudley Road Hospital]], Birmingham, where he taught medical students for the [[Membership of the Royal Colleges of Physicians of the United Kingdom|MRCP]], established an [[endoscopy]] service and began a 20-year study of the effects of [[alcoholic liver cirrhosis]].\n\nHe later held consultant positions at the [[St Ann's Hospital]] and the Prince of Wales Hospital in North London, and became the first chairman of the medical committee of [[Alcohol Change UK|Alcohol Concern]]. His book, ''ABC of Alcohol'', went through four editions.\n\n==Early life==\nAlexander Paton was born on 2 March 1924 in [[Allahabad]], India. His father, also called Alex, was an army colonel who had been awarded the [[Military Cross]]. His mother, Isabel Sybil Emma Grimwood Mears was the daughter of Sir [[Edward Grimwood Mears]], chief justice of the [[High Court of Allahabad]].<ref name=\"MunksRoll\">{{Cite web|url=http://munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk/Biography/Details/7146|title=Munks Roll Details for Alexander Paton|last=|first=|date=|website=munksroll.rcplondon.ac.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter completing his early education at [[Alleyn Court Prep School]], Essex, he gained a scholarship to [[Canford School]] in Dorset and subsequently gained admission to study medicine at [[St Thomas's Hospital Medical School]], London during [[The Blitz]].<ref name=\"MunksRoll\"/><ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/sep/27/alex-paton-obituary|title=Alex Paton obituary|last=Richmond|first=Caroline|date=27 September 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|access-date=4 September 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref name=\"BMJObituary\">{{Cite journal|last=Jain|first=Stephan|date=24 September 2015|title=Re: Alexander Paton|url=https://www.bmj.com/content/351/bmj.h5123/rr-5|journal=British Medical Journal|language=en|volume=351|pages=h5123|doi=10.1136/bmj.h5123|via=}}</ref>\n\n==Belsen==\n[[File:Group photo of London Medical students who went to Belsen Wellcome L0029073.jpg|thumb|Group photo of London Medical students who went to Belsen]]\nHe was one of the London medical students who were sent to [[Bergen-Belsen concentration camp]] in 1945, shortly after its liberation by the British troops, to assist [[Arnold Peter Meiklejohn]] in administering what was known as the \"starvation diet\" to the severely malnourished and dying inmates. Many of these inmates had such advanced malnutrition that they were intolerant of large, highly nutritious meals and the diet comprised small, frequent, bland meals which were much better tolerated.<ref name=Shepherd2005>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=FJ8h0vOBPR8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Student+volunteer+for+medical+relief+at+the+concentration+camp+Bergen-Belsen#v=onepage&q=student&f=false|title=AfterDaybreak: The Liberation of Belsen, 1945|last=Shephard|first=Ben|date=2005|page=130|publisher=Random House|isbn=9781409079644|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn his memoirs, published in the ''British Medical Journal'' in 1981,<ref name=MunksRoll/> he described how on 4 April 1945 there was a proposed trip to Holland for 12 St Thomas's students. He put his name down and on 12 April was at the [[The Landmark London|Hotel Grand Central at Marylebone]] collecting his kit. After a briefing by [[Richard Doll]], explaining how they were to feed the starving Dutch with an experimental mixture, they were asked to \"keep detailed records\".<ref name=\"Paton1981\">{{Cite journal|last=Patton|first=Aex|date=December 1981|title=Mission to Belsen 1945|journal=British Medical Journal|volume=283|issue=6307|pages=1656\u20131659|pmc=1507476|pmid=6797597|doi=10.1136/bmj.283.6307.1656}}</ref><ref name=Belsen>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bergenbelsen.co.uk/pages/Database/ReliefStaffAccount.asp?HeroesID=44&=44|title=Paton|last=|first=|date=|website=www.bergenbelsen.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Paton2005\">{{Cite journal|last=Paton|first=Alex|date=30 April 2005|title=After Daybreak: The Liberation of Belsen, 1945|journal=BMJ : British Medical Journal|volume=330|issue=7498|pages=1030|issn=0959-8138|pmc=557164|doi=10.1136/bmj.330.7498.1030}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 April, they were informed that the destination had changed to Belsen and they were rushed to [[Cirencester]], where they spent three \u201cfrustrating\u201d days. He recalled how the newspapers had already announced that \u201c100 students from nine London medical schools are being rushed to Germany\u201d. They arrived in Belsen on 2 May 1945 and on the following day began to clean up the huts in the camp and supervise feeding of inmates.<ref name=\"Paton1981\"/><ref name=Belsen/><ref name=\"Paton2005\"/>\n\nWith another student [[A. T. Cook]], they were one of the first to create a hospital from a hut.<ref name=Vella1984>{{Cite journal|last=Vella|first=E. E.|date=1984|title=Belsen: Medical Aspects of a World War 11 Concentration Camp|url=https://jramc.bmj.com/content/jramc/130/1/34.full.pdf|journal=[[Royal Army Medical Corps#Journal|Journal Royal Army Medical Corps]]|volume=130|issue=1|pages=34\u201359|via=|doi=10.1136/jramc-130-01-08|pmid=6371230}}</ref>\n\nUpon return, he landed at [[Croydon airport|Croydon]] on 29 May 1945 \u201cwith feelings that are too complicated to analyse at the moment\u201d.<ref name=Shepherd2005/><ref name=\"Paton1981\"/>\n\n==Career==\nPaton qualified in 1947 and was one of the first intake of doctors into the new [[NHS]].<ref name=Haga>{{Cite web|url=http://www.haga.co.uk/remembering-alex-paton/|title=Remembering Alex Paton|last=|first=|date=12 September 2016|website=HAGA|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 September 2019}}</ref>  After house officer posts he spent two years\u2019 doing national service in the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]] in [[Trieste]].  Following a post in [[Salisbury]] in 1950, and another at [[St Helier Hospital]] in 1951,<ref name=MunksRoll/> he became registrar to [[Sheila Sherlock]],<ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/> an expert in liver disease, at the [[Royal Postgraduate Medical School]], part of the [[Hammersmith Hospital]]. At his interview with Sherlock, she asked Paton \"are you prepared to push patients in a bed to the laboratory? You are? The job is yours\".<ref name=Richmond2002>{{Cite journal|last=Richmond|first=Caroline|date=19 January 2002|title=Dame Sheila Sherlock|journal=BMJ : British Medical Journal|volume=324|issue=7330|pages=174|issn=0959-8138|pmc=1122088|doi=10.1136/bmj.324.7330.174}}</ref> During this post, he kept a private diary in which he wrote about the research into liver disease, saying... \"we and anyone else at Hammersmith use subjects for experiments who will not necessarily benefit by them\"<ref name=Seldon2017>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=iGOhDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT169|title=TheWhistle-Blower: The Life of Maurice Pappworth: the story of one man's battle against the medical establishment|last=Seldon|first=Joanna|date=2017|publisher=University of Buckingham Press|isbn=9781-908684974|location=Buckingham|pages=|language=en|chapter=5. Breaking the Silence: A Rebel and his Cause}}</ref> and quoted his South African houseman as saying \"the beds are nothing more than an annexe to the medical laboratories\".<ref name=Hazelgrove2004>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NgvQHQqA1HkC&pg=PA188|title=Twentiethcentury ethics of human subjects research: historical perspectives on values, practices, and regulations|last=Hazelgrove|first=Jenny|date=2004|publisher=Franz Steiner Verlag|isbn=9783515084550|editor-last=Roelcke|editor-first=Volker|location=|pages=188|language=en|chapter=British Research Ethics after the Second World War: The Controversy at the British Postgraduate Medical School, Hammersmith Hospital}}</ref><ref nameO'Mahony2019>{{Cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ynJfDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT43|title=Can Medicine Be Cured?: The Corruption of a Profession|last=O'Mahony|first=Seamus|date=2019|publisher=Head of Zeus Ltd|isbn=9781788544535|location=|pages=|language=en|chapter=3. Fifty Golden Years}}</ref>\n\nHe completed his [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]] at [[Yale University]] on the topic of neurology in [[diabetes mellitus]].<ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/> In 1959, he was appointed consultant physician  to [[City Hospital, Birmingham|Dudley Road Hospital]], Birmingham, where his main focus was on [[emergency medicine]],<ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/> [[internal medicine]] and the liver.<ref name=\"BMJObituary\"/> Here he taught postgraduate medical students who were preparing for the [[Membership of the Royal Colleges of Physicians of the United Kingdom|MRCP]] examination, established an [[endoscopy]] service and began a 20-year study of the effects of [[alcoholic liver cirrhosis]].<ref name=MunksRoll/><ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/>\n\nIn 1973, he took a one-year [[sabbatical]] as a visiting professor of medicine in [[Baghdad]].<ref name=MunksRoll/><ref name=Haga/>\n\nIn 1981 he returned to London and became postgraduate [[Dean (education)|Dean]] for [[North West London Hospitals NHS Trust|North-West London hospitals]].<ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/> He took up consultant positions at the [[St Ann's Hospital]] and the Prince of Wales Hospital in North London, and became the first chairman of the medical committee of [[Alcohol Change UK|Alcohol Concern]].<ref name=MunksRoll/>\n\nIn the ''British Medical Journal'''s ''[[BMJ ABC Series|ABC of Alcohol]]'', which he edited,<ref name=Haga/> Paton described people's patterns of drinking and its association with genetic, constitutional and environmental factors, and explained why women were more susceptible to the effects of alcohol than men.<ref name=\"Moriarty\"/> In addition he highlighted how alcohol misuse was easily missed in the elderly.<ref name=\"Moriarty\">{{Cite journal|last=Moriarty|first=Kieran|date=January 2006|title=ABC of Alcohol (4th edn)|journal=Annals of the Royal College of Surgeons of England|language=en|volume=88|issue=1|pages=84\u201385|doi=10.1308/rcsann.2006.88.1.84b|pmc=1963615}}</ref><ref name=cisa>{{Cite web|url=http://en.cisa.org.br/artigo/89/the-absorption-of-alcohol-in-the.php|title=The absorption of alcohol in the body|last=Paton|first=Alex|date=|website=en.cisa.org.br|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=8 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn reviewing the book ''Medical Nemesis'' by [[Ivan Illich]], he was one of the few reviewers supporting Illich, saying that \u201chis argument is closely reasoned, sometimes obscure, often exasperating, but never dull, and fully documented\u201d.<ref name=RCSEdin2016>{{Cite journal|last=O\u2019Mahony|first=S.|date=2016|title=Medical Nemesis 40 years on: the enduring legacy of Ivan Illich|url=https://www.rcpe.ac.uk/sites/default/files/jrcpe_46_2_omahony_0.pdf|journal=Royal College of Physicians Edinburgh|volume=46|issue=2|pages=134\u2013139|via=|doi=10.4997/JRCPE.2016.214|pmid=27929580}}</ref>\n\nIn 1987, he retired and for the next three years worked at the addictions unit at the [[Warneford Hospital]], Oxford.<ref name=MunksRoll/>\n\n==Other roles==\nPaton was a member of the Association of Physicians, the [[Medical Research Society]], Haringey Health Authority, the scholarship committee of the Wingate Foundation, the [[Pensions Appeal Tribunal]] of which he later became chairman, and the [[Royal College of Physicians]] of which he was examiner and regional adviser. For seven years he was secretary of the West Midlands Physicians Association. He also chaired the travelling fellowships committee of the [[King\u2019s Fund]].<ref name=MunksRoll/>\n\n==Personal and family==\nIn 1947 he married Phyllis Ann Jennifer Pepys, better known as Ann, a nurse and descendant of [[Samuel Pepys]]' cousin and [[Sir Lucas Pepys]].<ref name=MunksRoll/><ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/> They later retired to rural Oxfordshire together.<ref name=MunksRoll/> [[Margaret Tempest]] became his step-grand mother in 1951, when she married his grandfather.<ref name=MunksRoll/><ref name=Russen>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ipswichstar.co.uk/news/ipswich-icons-artist-margaret-mary-tempest-brought-little-grey-rabbit-to-life-1-4805930|title=Ipswich Icons - Artist Margaret Mary Tempest brought Little Grey Rabbit to life|last=Russen|first=Mervyn|date=5 December 2016|website=Ipswich Star|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=SuffolkArtists>{{Cite web|url=https://suffolkartists.co.uk/index.cgi?choice=painter&pid=787|title=Suffolk Artists - TEMPEST, Margaret Mary|last=|first=|date=|website=suffolkartists.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=Paton>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sandscoxcharity.uk/alexander-paton|title=Alexander Paton|last=Paton|first=Alexander|date=|website=Sands Cox Charity|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nHe played tennis, enjoyed climbing, skiing, walking, classical music, the arts, photography, natural history, church architecture and travelling. He visited [[Antarctica]] twice.<ref name=MunksRoll/>\n\nOne son, Charles, died in 1973 and his wife Ann died in 2008.<ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/> They had two other sons, Alex and Anthony, and two daughters, Clare and Rachel.<ref name=MunksRoll/>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nPaton died on 12 September 2015.<ref name=MunksRoll/><ref name=\"BMJObituary\"/> \n\nHis memoirs are included in the 2005 book ''After Daybreak: The Liberation of Belsen, 1945'' by [[Ben Shephard (historian)|Ben Shephard]].<ref name=\"Paton2005\"/> He was portrayed in the 2007 feature-length drama titled ''[[The Relief of Belsen]]'' in which he quotes \"in my hut there were no deaths today, sir\".<ref name=\"IMBb\">{{Citation|last=|first=|title=The Relief of Belsen|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0950502/characters/nm2447755?ref_=tt_cl_t11|volume=|pages=|access-date=4 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=BFI>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2bd9c0d0e0|title=Henry Pettigrew|last=|first=|date=|website=[[British Film Institute]]|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\nPaton wrote a number of articles for newspapers, edited work in the ''British Medical Journal'' for 50 years and was a member of [[Stephen Lock]]'s BMJ writing workshops. He also wrote and edited the BMJ's publication ''ABC of Alcohol'', which went through four editions.<ref name=MunksRoll/> On the confusion between 'effect' and 'affect', he wrote \"these words are commonly used, and misuse may seriously affect (alter) meaning\".<ref name=Goodman2014>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=1KsZBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA75&dq=liver+disease+alex+paton#v=onepage&q=liver%20disease%20alex%20paton&f=false|title=MedicalWriting|last=Goodman|first=Neville W.|last2=Edwards|first2=Martin B.|date=2014|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|isbn=9781107628151|edition=4th|location=|pages=75|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHis time in Baghdad led him to write about the [[Marsh Arabs]].<ref name=\"CarolineRichmond2015\"/>\n\n===Articles===\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2540780/pdf/bmj00450-0041.pdf \u201cWay with Words\u201d], ''British Medical Journal'', Vol. 309, 23 July 1994, p.&nbsp;253. {{PMID|7832842}} {{doi|10.1136/bmj.309.6949.249}}\n*[https://academic.oup.com/alcalc/article/34/4/502/188038 \"Reflections on Alcohol in the Young\"], ''[[Alcohol and Alcoholism]]'', Vol. 34, Issue 4 (1 July 1999), pp.&nbsp;502\u2013505. {{doi|10.1093/alcalc/34.4.502}}\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC543875/pdf/bmj33000085.pdf \"Alcohol in the Body\"], ''British Medical Journal'', Vol. 330, 8 January 2005, pp.&nbsp;85\u201387. {{PMID|15637372}} {{doi|10.1136/bmj.330.7482.85}}\n*[https://www.magonlinelibrary.com/doi/abs/10.12968/hosp.2000.61.3.1290 \"Alcohol: Matters of life and death\"], ''Hospital Medicine'', Vol. 61, No. 3 (28 Sep 2013). {{doi|10.12968/hosp.2000.61.3.1290}}\n\n===Books===\n*''Liver Disease''. [[Heinemann (publisher)|William Heinemann]], London, 1969. {{ISBN|0433247207}}\n*''[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=AXvAY3ewtQQC&lpg=PP1&dq=alex%20paton%20gastroenterology&pg=PP4#v=onepage&q&f=false ABC of Alcohol]''. [[Blackwell Publishing]], Oxford, 1982. (Four editions, co-edited with Robin Touquet)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/?term=Alex+paton ''British Medical Journal'' articles by Paton]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paton, Alex (physician)}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[